{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_clash_ver01/data/sn84020351/00414219494/1930080201/0256.xml":{"full_text":"LA SENTINELLA\n6\nItala Gente\nRAFFAELLO LAMBRUSCHINI\nENGLISH SECTION\nBy AREL\nIl benefico movimento di idee\nche distinse la Toscana dell'ot\ntocento fu in gran parte opera\ndel genovese abate Lambruschi\nni, il quale parve a un certo mo\nmento contrapporsi allo zio, il\nfamoso cardinale segretario di\nStato di Gregorio VI e uomo di\nfiducia di Mettermeli, non soloJ\ncome riformatore politico ma ad\ndirittura quale riformatore reli-J\ngioso per quell'orbita del catto\nlicesimo, per quanto a Firenze\n10 chiamassero scherzosamente\n\"luterino\".\n\"Quanto a me\" scriveva\ninfatti il 15 novembre 1848 a\nNiccol\u00f2 Puccini \"credo venuto\n11 momento d'alzar pi\u00f9 che mai\nla bandiera della religione di\nGes\u00f9 Cristo, perci\u00f2 la vera cat\ntolica; e quello .che scriver\u00f2,\nsar\u00e0 a questo fine. O mi bruce\nranno come Savonarola, o far\u00f2\ndel bene all'Italia e al mondo\".\nMa l'illusione in lui stesso e\nnegli amici fu di breve durata,\ne il Lambruschini fu sempre e\nrimase, come si defini' una volta\nda s\u00e8, \"uno di quelli che il Saint\nSimon chiamava \"Divulgatori\",\ni quali fanno del bene anch'essi,\ne ci vogliono, ma non mandano\navanti la scienza\".\nEppure proprio come divulga--\ntore, e poi anche come educatore,\negli ebbe un'influenza enorme\nsullo spirito pubblico della To\nscana del suo tempo.\nNato a Genova il 14 Agosto\n1788, il Lambruschini a 17 anni\nvesti l'abito talare e and\u00f2 a stu\ndiare a Rova presso lo zio. Ma\nquivi perse ogni amore, se mai\nne aveva, per la carriera eccle\nsiastica e dopo la restaurazione\nand\u00f2 a stabilirsi in Toscana con\nsuo padre, che aveva comprato\npresso Figline la villa, divenuta\npoi famosa, di. San Cerbone.\nA quella villa egli rimase fe\ndele sino alla morte, pur la\nsciandola; di frequente per Fi\nrenze, i primi anni per seguire\ncorsi di scienze, in seguito per\nlavorare aH'\"Aritologia\", di cui\nfu uno dei maggiori e migliori\nesponenti, e al \"Giornale Agra\nrio\" da lui fondato nel Gennaio\n1827, e per cooperare col cena\ncolo dei Georgofili specialmen\nte con Gino Capponi) alla rina\nscita economica della Toscana.\nFu opera sua che sorse in To\nscana la prima Cassa di Rispar\nmio, nel 1829, e per iniziativa\nsua si ebbero col\u00e0 numerosi espe\nrimenti agricoli, fra cui l'intro\nduzione del baco da seta.\nEgli stesso del resto a San\nCerbone si occupava con passio\nne di agricoltura pratica. Ma non\nsoltanto di questo: che nel 1830\nfond\u00f2 nella sua villa un piccolo\ncollegio per giovani della buona\nsociet\u00e0, rinnovando la nobile tra\ndizione di Vittorino da Feltre.\nDa questa nuova e intensa espe\nrienza personale, a cui si dedic\u00f2\nquasi interamente dopo la sop\npressione dell'\"Antologia\", nac\nque un nuovo periodico che ebbe\nrapida diffusione in tutta l'Ita\nlia, la \"Guida dell'educatore\",\ncome pi\u00f9 tardi i famosi due\nlibri \"Dell'educazione\".\nL'educazione egli fondava sul\nl'insegnamento religioso, per\nfarne a sua volta il fondamento\ndella rinascita nazionale. Vero\nmaestro di patriottismo egli era\ne con la parola e col copioso car\nteggio, non -potendolo con la\nstampa e perci\u00f2 ad ogni occasio\nne propizia egli era pronto a la\nsciare il suo ritiro, non negando\nmai alla coperta propaganda na\nzionale l'autorit\u00e0 del suo nome.\nCosi presi\u00e8dette il primo Con\ngresso degli Scienziati a Firen\nze ed intervenne a tutti gli altri.\nScoppiata la prima guerra d'in\ndipendenza, benedisse gli allievi\nche partivano volontari per la\nLombardia e parl\u00f2 loro lo stesso\nlinguaggio da \"crociato\" del ge\nnerale Durando: \"Noi combatte\nremo, noi vinceremo. Dio \u00e8 con\nnoi. Dio ha detto: l'Italia sia\nlibera. Ora non si pensi che a\nscacciare l'Austriaco\". Parte\ncip\u00f2 di poi, con Ricasoli e Sanva\ngnoli, alla creazione della \"Pa\ntria\", organo moderato, fu elet\nto deputato all'assemblea tosca\nna e vice presidente della stes\nstessa, e da ultimo deputato alla\nCostituente ma dopo la fuga del\ngranduca si ritir\u00f2 a San Cerbone,\nper non muoversi quasi mai pi\u00f9\nfino al 1859. Quell'anno fu elet\nto deputato alla nuova assem\nblea toscana e nell'ottobre nomi\nnato ispettore generale delle\nscuole. Creato l'Istituto di Stu\ndi Superiori, ne fu nominato\nprofessore di padagogia e sopra\nintendente, mentre nel '67 fu no\nminato presidente dei Georgofili\ne nel '69 arciconsole della Crusca.\nA tutti gli uffici egli attese\nsempre col massimo zelo come a\nquello di senatore conferitogli il\n23 Marzo 1860 (una successiva\nelezione a deputato pel collegio\ndi Cagli all' Vili legislatura fu\nperci\u00f2 annullata) perch\u00e8 per lui,\ncome soleva dire, \"ristarsi era\nmorire\". Negli ultimi anni at\ntese con Augusto Conti ed altri\nalla redazione del giornale \"La\nfamiglia e la scuola\" e scrisse i\n\"Dialoghi sulla- istruzione\", che\npubblic\u00f2 nel 1871. Colto da pa\nralisi mori T8 Marzo nel 1873 e\nfu sepolto, secondo che aveva\npredisposto, con le insegne sacer\ndotali. Fino all'ultimo fu assisti\nto sempre da una grande fede\nnell'Italia.\nHAPPINESS IN WISDOM\nBy Dr. Joseph Pantaleone\nwonder how many people have ever asked themselves this\nmost fundamental of all questions: What is really worth while in\nlife and what way of living can pay us more than any other at our\nchoice? This, above all questions, should be uppermost in the\nminds of all persons bent upon getting the greatest happiness and\nsatisfaction which life can offer. Yet how few are the people\nwho have seriously asked themselves this all important question!\nWe are now considering that which in philosophy is known as\nthe ethical problem: \"What is good; what is bad?\" Those\namong us who are sincerely and deeply interested in getting the\nmost out of our brief earthly existence may be interested in a\nshort summary of those things which the world's greatest minds\nhave considered most worth while in life and as capable of yield\ning the most permanent satisfaction andthe greatest joys and\nthrills attainable in this world. Certainly, for every man there\nis no more important subject to consider than this.\nThroughout the ages, all the great constructive master minds\nhave agreed on certain fundamental principles. The secret of hap\npiness is simplicity itself. It is a four-fold truth; the passionate\npursuit of truth, beauty, love, and goodness, and it is the essence\nof all great philosophies and religions. From Confucius to Buddha,\nlife has been one, the secret of the Kingdom of Heaven to be\nestablished on this earth within our own minds and hearts.\nBy the pursuit of beauty, I mean the passionate love of all\nthe fine arts and the love of truth and goodness lor its own -sake.\nBy the pursuit of truth is meant the study and deep interest\nin all of life's marvelous and 'infinitely varied manifestations;\nit is the vast theatre of life in all its forms in which we should\nail be profoundly interested.\nBy goodness is meant the law of joy in work, the law of the\ngolden rule, the law of universal love, sympathy, kindness, and\ninfinite charity. It is the sermon on the mount applied in pract\nical life.\nBy love is meant the universal love of all things, all people,\nall ages, all animals, and also true family love.\nHere, then, in a few words we have, as I say, the essence of\nall great philosophies the meaning of human life and the secret\nof happiness. This is why the wise man is extremely happy and the\nman of understanding rejoices deeply in the infinite treasury he\nhas inherited and is privileged to enjoy in this life and he\nthanks God and is glad to be alive.\nThere isn't a single one among us wha cannot practice and\ncultivate to some extent, at least, these supremely valuable ideals.\nUn medicante accosta una si\ngnora questa gli d\u00e0 la sua carta\nda visita, dicendogli:\nVenite a trovarmi. Vi sa\nranno degli abiti usati da pren\ndere. Dopo tre giorni la signora in\ncontra il mendicante:\nPerch\u00e8 non siete venuto?\nIl mendicante, mostrando il\nbiglietto da visita, con tutta\ncortesia\nDomando scusa, ma qui\ndice: \"Ricevimenti il gioveri\".\nAspettavo a giovedi.\nIndirizzi utili\nCASA DEI FIGiM D'ITALIA\n474 E. Washington Ave.\nCXiUB CASFRTA NAPOLI\n201 North Washington Avenue\nIXTKRNATIONAL INSTITUTE\n56 Beach Street\nUFFICIO del GIORNALE\n\"LA SENTINELLA\"\n641 EkLBt Washington Avenue\nCHIESA ITALIANA DEL ROSARIO.\n385 E. Washington Ave.\nCHIESA ITALIANA\ndi SAN RAFFAELE\nOak Street\nDELEGAZIONE DELLA CROCE\nROSSA ITALIANA\n6 30 E. Washington Ave.\nCHIESA ITALIANA del CALVARIO\n220 Centre Street\nPROSPERITY IS RETURNING\nThe prospects for business revival are encouraging. It is re\ncognized every where that the past two weeks has had a good\neffect on business. Capital is being slowly released and employ\nment is gradually increasing. Normal business -conditions are re\nturning gradually. They will come slowly as the depression came.\nBy early fall, every indication points, there will be much improve\nment in the general business conditions.\nA year ago the stock markets were a chief factor in business.\nThe whole country were engaged in activities that were little\nshort of gambling. The volume of stock trading today shows that\nthe public has deserted a game at which it was decisively beaten.\nInstead money is being used in legitimate business, and the\niatter will shortly show the effects of such constructive effort.\nThe country's prosperity is being rebuilt. When the project is\nundertaken seriously it is only a short time until results become\napparent in the reduction of unemployment and a more healthy\ntone in all kinds of useful commerce.\nVICIOUS ANIMALS ARE A MENACE\nWe cannot understanding the point of view of the good\ncitizen who will keep on his premises a vicious animal to menace\nthe persons, and even possibly the lives, of others. We say \"good\ncitizens\" advisedly. We know there are perfectly fine people, good\nneighbors and friends, who do that very thing. Any person\nproceeding about his business in a public place, or entering upon\nthe property of others for legitimate purposes, should not be\nsubjected to the attack from an ugly dog. No owner thinks his\ndog is vicious; that is a condition to be recognized. The real dog\nlover, while willing to consider complaints regarding his children,\nis sure his dog has a perfect disposition. He believes that in the\nface of evidence. We are all familiar with the old speaeh of\nSenator George Vest of Missouri who described the dog as a man's\nmost faithful friend. That is more or less true. That does not\nmake it reasonable that human beings be made liable to attack\nby animals large enough \"in some cases to kill a grown man. It\nseems to us that even a threat by a dog against a person going\nabout his business should be all that is required to call for the\npermanent removal of such an animal. A dog which actually bites\na person except under cases of extreme provocation cannot be\nexcused, and the sooner it is disposed of the better.\nUP TO THE INDIVIDUAL\nSlack times are mostly the result of a mental attitude on the\npart of the public, good times are probably never as good as\npeople say they are quiet periods are never as bad as reported.\nThe money difference between good times and bad times is\nonly a small fraction of the total trade of a community. The best\nway to keep employment normal is to have necessary work done\nwhen activity slows up.\nThis is \u00e0 matter for the individual. And if each of, usN is\ndetermined to do our part we are likely to keep a pretty level\nemployment situation.\nSUCH IS LIFE\nA Connecticut man who says he has moved ten times in the\npast ten years believes that there is a very distinct advantage in\nowning one's home. The moving in each instance has cost his$50,\nand his rent has cost him an average ,of $1 a day, a total of $360\nI for the year or $3,600 for ten years. \"And all I have to show for\ni it\", he says, \"is a pile of rent receipts, and, scars on my furniture.\"\nIt does seem that a person should have something more than to\nshow tor an expenditure ot more than $6,000.\nA few flowers and some shrubbery about your premises\nwill help wonderfully towards brightening up things, not only\nfor the occupants of your home but for all passers by as well. Do\nyour part, however small it may be, toward helping to make your\nplace beautiful.\nEarly to bed and early to rise, out the weeds and swat the\nflies; mind your own business, tell no lies, don't get gay and\ndeceive your wife, pay your debts, use enterprise and buy at home\nfrom hose who advertise.\nSI CERCA UN AGENTE che\ncapisce e parla fluentemente\nla lingua italiana pe,r fare\ndelle vendite speciali al di\nfuori. Si pu\u00f2 guadagnare una\nbuona paga. Rivolgersi da\nThe Hadley Co., Broad e John\nSts. e domandare di Mr. J. H.\nSpeers.\nBLUE RIBBON\nCarri Scelti\n1926 Chevrolet Coach $30.00\n1924 Studebaker Coach $95.00\n1926 Chrysler Sedan $125.00\n1926 Oldsmobile Coupe $150.00\n1927 Chevrolet Coach $150.00\n1926 Dodge Sedan $150.00\n1926 Studebaker Coach $195.00\n1927 Dodge Sedan $225.00\n1926 Loco jr. 8\" Sedan $225.00\n1925 Buick Coach $235.00\n1928 Durant Coach $235.00\n1928 Whippet Coach $235.00\n1928 Chevrolet Coupe $325.00\n1928 Chevrolet R'dster $325.00\n1928 Chrysler Sedan $325.00\n1926 Nash Coach $325.00\n1928 Pontiac Coac $325.00\n1928 Dodge \"6\" Sedan $475.00\nE MOLTI ALTRI CARRI\nThe Blue Ribbon Garage\n180 Cannon Street\n25 Anni alPistesso indirizzo\nTel. Noble: 7102\nAperto Di Sera\nUN ECCELLENTE INVESTI-;\nMENTO. Abbiamo 6 Stores e\ndue appartamenti, in una pro\npriet\u00e0, ad un angolo di North\nMain St. Siamo disposti a\nvendere a prezzo basso ad un\nbuon cliente. Per informazioni\ntelefonate Barnum 825.\nSI .VENDE una Stufa Glenwood\na Carbone e Gas Modello K -Usata\nsolo 5 anni Sembra\nnuova. Un corredo di